{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}
'''''Eight Poems''''' is a 1962 poetry collection by the American poet [[Marianne Moore]], with illustrations by [[Robert Andrew Parker]]. It was published by the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York City. Only 195 copies were produced; each was signed by Moore and Parker.<ref name="Leavell2013">{{cite book|author=Linda Leavell|title=Holding On Upside Down: The Life and Work of Marianne Moore|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZetmAgAAQBAJ|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-30183-6|page=177}}</ref>
Each of Moore's poems in the volume was accompanied by an image from Parker. In his 2001 book ''Material Modernism: The Politics of the Page'', the literary critic [[George Bornstein]] commented on the juxtaposition of Moore's poem "The Fish" and Parker's drawing in ''Eight Poems''. Bornstein wrote that "One can no longer interpret "The Fish" as military reinforcements in the First World War; they steadfastly remain the delicate creatures of Parker's accompanying watercolor. A poem that started out as an anti-military poem in an anti-war journal has metamorphosed into a commodified (sic) aesthetic object".<ref name="Bornstein2001">{{cite book|author=George Bornstein|title=Material Modernism: The Politics of the Page|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6tw1ZwOnLj0C|date=5 February 2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-66154-6|page=103}}</ref>
==Poems== *"The Plumet Basilisk" *"The Fish" *"'He Digesteth Harde Yron'" *"A Jelly-Fish" *"New York" *"The Pangolin" *"The Monkeys" *"Nevertheless"
==References== {{Reflist}}
[[Category:1962 books]] [[Category:American poetry collections]] [[Category:Museum of Modern Art (New York)]] [[Category:Poetry by Marianne Moore]]

The '''Father Sebastian Englert Anthropological Museum''' is a [[museum]] in the town of [[Hanga Roa]] on [[Rapa Nui]] ([[Easter Island]]) in [[Chilean Polynesia]]. Named for the [[Bavaria]]n missionary, Fr. [[Sebastian Englert]], [[O.F.M. Cap.|OFM Cap.]], the museum was founded in 1973 and is dedicated to the conservation of the Rapa Nui cultural patrimony. The museum is administered by the [[Chilean Directorate of Libraries, Archives and Museums]] (DiBAM) and houses the [[William Mulloy Library]].<ref>[http://www.museorapanui.cl/Biblioteca/index.php William Mulloy Library], Chile.</ref>
The museum houses the only female [[mo‘ai]], as well as one of the coral eyes that were placed in the mo‘ai.{{citation needed|date=July 2011}} There are wood statuettes, a photographic collection, archives of traditional music, and a three-thousand-volume library.
[[File:Museo Sebastian Englert.JPG|thumb|Museo Antropologico P. Sebastian Englert, Rapa Nui (Easter Island)]]
